`crates/ctx-cage/src/bin/` holds the two CLI entry points for ctx-cage: `ctx_cage.rs`, a generic orchestrator that gates billed modes behind an explicit flag/env var, and `ctx_run.rs`, a pre-authorized wrapper (`ctx-run`) where invocation itself is the spend consent, aimed at interactive/task sessions with an optional post-run summary refresh. `ctx_run/` is a supporting subdirectory for the latter binary's credentials-file loading.

Both top-level binaries independently implement the same sibling-binary resolution pattern (`ctx-verify`, `ctx-context`, `ctx-scan` derived from the current exe's directory, overridable via `CTX_VERIFY_BIN`/`CTX_CONTEXT_BIN`/`CTX_SCAN_BIN`) and both build a `Resolved` struct handed to `ctx_cage::lifecycle::execute` — if the resolution or lifecycle contract changes, update both binaries in lockstep. Neither binary ever passes an API key or agent-cmd config into the sandboxed/cage process itself; `ctx_run.rs` and `ctx_run/env_file.rs` share the invariant that credentials loaded from `~/.config/ctx/env` only ever reach the summarizer child process, never the cage's own environment.

`ctx_cage.rs` is the general-purpose, explicitly-gated entry point; `ctx_run.rs` is the specialized, pre-authorized one for the common billed workflow, with its own credential-loading logic split into the `ctx_run/` subdirectory.

intent_divergence: no intent.md exists for this directory, so no claim can be checked against it.